COUNTLESS are the graves of saints I have seen in the city of Romulus, Valerian, Christ’s dedicated servant. You ask for the inscriptions cut on their tombs, and their individual names, but it is hard for me to be able to repeat them. Such great multitudes of the righteous did ungodly rage devour while Trojan Rome still worshipped the gods of her fathers. Many a grave is lettered and tells the · martyr's name or bears some epitaph, but there are mute marbles too, which shut up the tombs in silence and only indicate the number3 you may learn what masses of men's bodies lie gathered together in heaps, but read the name of none of them.
